# Creating a New GitHub Repo from Your PC

Use this when you have a project folder on your PC and want to push it to GitHub for the first time.

---

## The correct order — never skip a step

```
git init → git add . → git commit → gh repo create
```

---

## Step-by-step with explanations

### 1. `git init`

```bash
git init
```

**What it does:** Initialises a brand-new Git repository inside your current folder.  
This creates a hidden `.git/` folder that Git uses to track all your changes.

> ⚠️ Always run this first. Running `git add .` before `git init` will throw an error — Git doesn't exist in the folder yet.

---

### 2. `git add .`

```bash
git add .
```

**What it does:** Stages all files in the folder, marking them as ready to be committed.  
The `.` means "everything in this folder and all subfolders."

> Think of it as telling Git: *"I want to include all these files in my next snapshot."*

---

### 3. `git commit -m "init"`

```bash
git commit -m "init"
```

**What it does:** Saves a snapshot of all your staged files with a message describing the change.  
`"init"` is the message — you can write anything, but `"init"` is the standard first-commit message.

> You must commit before pushing. GitHub needs at least one commit to create the repo from.

---

### 4. `gh repo create`

```bash
gh repo create earnings2 --public --source=. --push
```

**What it does:** Creates a new repo on GitHub AND pushes your local commit to it in one command.

| Part | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `earnings2` | The name of the new GitHub repo |
| `--public` | Makes the repo publicly visible (use `--private` to hide it) |
| `--source=.` | Tells GitHub CLI to use the current folder as the source — **do not forget this** |
| `--push` | Automatically pushes your commits to GitHub right after creating the repo |

> ⚠️ `--source=.` is required. Without it, the command creates an empty repo on GitHub but does not link or push your local files.

---

## Full sequence — copy-paste ready

```bash
git init
git add .
git commit -m "init"
gh repo create YOUR-REPO-NAME --public --source=. --push
```

Replace `YOUR-REPO-NAME` with the name you want for the repo on GitHub.

---

## Common mistakes

| Mistake | What happens | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| Skipping `git init` | `git add .` fails — no Git repo exists yet | Always run `git init` first |
| Forgetting `--source=.` | Repo is created on GitHub but your files are not pushed | Re-run with `--source=.` included |
| Forgetting `git commit` before `gh repo create` | Push fails — nothing to push | Run `git add .` and `git commit` first |

---

## This vs. cloning an existing repo

| Situation | Command to start with |
|-----------|----------------------|
| **New project on your PC** → push to GitHub | `git init` ← you are here |
| **Existing repo on GitHub** → download to your PC | `git clone <url>` |
